{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ki63cWXHdDviaA8PEm2Nkw","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/9-5-multi-stack-docs-remaining-consumers.md`.\n\n**What was done:**\n- Overwrote the existing skeletal story file with a complete story definition including 8 acceptance criteria (all tagged `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->`), 9 task groups with subtasks, full dev notes with architecture patterns, current code analysis, design decisions, and file change inventory.\n\n**Key findings during analysis:**\n- AC2 (`getStackLabel` with array) and AC3 (`getProjectName` multi-file) are **already implemented** in the current codebase. The story notes this explicitly so the dev agent verifies rather than re-implements.\n- The original epic had 5 ACs. I expanded to 8 to cover the full scope: `scaffoldDocs` passthrough (AC5), README template (AC6), teardown (AC7), and regression (AC8) were implicit in the technical notes but not called out as ACs.\n- `verify/env.ts` does NOT use `state.stack` — it calls `detectStack()` directly. AC4 was rewritten to reflect the actual change needed (`detectStacks()` instead of `detectStack()`).\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Ambiguity in epic AC4:** The original epic says \"verify/env.ts checks... uses `stacks.includes('nodejs')` instead of `stack === 'nodejs'`\", implying state-based lookup. But `verify/env.ts` never reads from state — it calls `detectStack(projectDir)` directly. The AC was rewritten to reflect the actual code path: switching from `detectStack()` to `detectStacks()` in `detectProjectType()`.\n- **ACs already satisfied:** AC2 and AC3 from the epic are already implemented (getStackLabel handles arrays since story 9-3, getProjectName already tries package.json then Cargo.toml). These are kept as ACs to verify-not-reimplement, which the dev notes call out explicitly.\n- **`docs-scaffold.ts` file size risk:** Currently 229 lines, limit is 300. Adding multi-stack AGENTS.md generation (~30-40 lines) brings it close to the ceiling. The story notes extraction as a contingency.\n- **No `readme.test.ts` found:** The templates directory may not have a test file for `readme.ts`. Task 7 may require creating a new test file. This is noted in the files-to-change list."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a24a31b267818bce3 (use SendMessage with to: 'a24a31b267818bce3' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 51340\ntool_uses: 34\nduration_ms: 169760</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"58ae4f51-bff6-4a66-807a-d4f10c8bdaa3","uuid":"5a33c887-05b8-4319-a0c2-0eb6c32babdc","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:41:28.225Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 9-5-multi-stack-docs-remaining-consumers. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a24a31b267818bce3","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/9-5-multi-stack-docs-remaining-consumers.md`.\n\n**What was done:**\n- Overwrote the existing skeletal story file with a complete story definition including 8 acceptance criteria (all tagged `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->`), 9 task groups with subtasks, full dev notes with architecture patterns, current code analysis, design decisions, and file change inventory.\n\n**Key findings during analysis:**\n- AC2 (`getStackLabel` with array) and AC3 (`getProjectName` multi-file) are **already implemented** in the current codebase. The story notes this explicitly so the dev agent verifies rather than re-implements.\n- The original epic had 5 ACs. I expanded to 8 to cover the full scope: `scaffoldDocs` passthrough (AC5), README template (AC6), teardown (AC7), and regression (AC8) were implicit in the technical notes but not called out as ACs.\n- `verify/env.ts` does NOT use `state.stack` — it calls `detectStack()` directly. AC4 was rewritten to reflect the actual change needed (`detectStacks()` instead of `detectStack()`).\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Ambiguity in epic AC4:** The original epic says \"verify/env.ts checks... uses `stacks.includes('nodejs')` instead of `stack === 'nodejs'`\", implying state-based lookup. But `verify/env.ts` never reads from state — it calls `detectStack(projectDir)` directly. The AC was rewritten to reflect the actual code path: switching from `detectStack()` to `detectStacks()` in `detectProjectType()`.\n- **ACs already satisfied:** AC2 and AC3 from the epic are already implemented (getStackLabel handles arrays since story 9-3, getProjectName already tries package.json then Cargo.toml). These are kept as ACs to verify-not-reimplement, which the dev notes call out explicitly.\n- **`docs-scaffold.ts` file size risk:** Currently 229 lines, limit is 300. Adding multi-stack AGENTS.md generation (~30-40 lines) brings it close to the ceiling. The story notes extraction as a contingency.\n- **No `readme.test.ts` found:** The templates directory may not have a test file for `readme.ts`. Task 7 may require creating a new test file. This is noted in the files-to-change list."}],"totalDurationMs":169760,"totalTokens":51340,"totalToolUseCount":34,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4483,"cache_read_input_tokens":46259,"output_tokens":597,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4483},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
